\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau|US Census Bureau]], the county has a total area of {{convert|1581|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|568|sqmi}} is land and {{convert|1014|sqmi}} (64%) is water.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/maps-data/data/docs/gazetteer/counties_list_26.txt|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113024015/http://www.census.gov/geo/maps-data/data/docs/gazetteer/counties_list_26.txt |url-status=dead|archive-date=November 13, 2013|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=September 19, 2014|date=August 22, 2012|title=2010 Census Gazetteer Files}}</ref>\n\nThe county borders the state of [[Indiana]] to the South and includes a portion of [[Lake Michigan]] to the West.\n\nThe [[St. Joseph River (Lake Michigan)|St. Joseph River]] is a major geographical feature, flowing mostly north and west through the county from [[Niles, Michigan|Niles]] to its mouth on Lake Michigan at [[St. Joseph, Michigan|St. Joseph]]. The southwest of the county is drained by the [[Galien River]] and its tributaries. [[Paw Paw Lake]] is in the north of the county, along with the [[Paw Paw River]], which flows into the St. Joseph River just before it enters Lake Michigan. A tiny portion along the Indiana state line is drained by small tributaries of the [[Kankakee River]], which ultimately flows into the [[Mississippi River]]. This is one of two areas of Michigan drained by the Mississippi River, the other being an area of Michigan's [[Upper Peninsula]] near the [[Wisconsin]] border.\n\n===Major highways===\n*{{jct|state=MI|I|94}} \u2013 runs north along the western edge of the county near Lake Michigan. Turns inland to skirt the [[St. Joseph, Michigan|St. Joseph]]/[[Benton Harbor, Michigan|Benton Harbor]] urban area. Runs east to [[Kalamazoo, Michigan|Kalamazoo]]. Business Loop 94 passes through downtown Benton Harbor and St. Joseph.\n*{{jct|state=MI|BL|94|dab1=Benton_Harbor-St._Joseph}} \u2013 runs through St. Joseph and Benton Harbor.\n*{{jct|country=USA|I|196}} \u2013 from its intersection with I-94 east of Benton Harbor, runs north to [[Holland, Michigan|Holland]], then east to [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]].\n*{{jct|state=MI|US|12}} \u2013 runs east\u2013west through the southern portion of the county from south of Niles through [[Three Oaks, Michigan|Three Oaks]] to [[New Buffalo, Michigan|New Buffalo]] and [[Michiana, Michigan]]. From Berrien County it connects with [[Michigan City, Indiana]].\n*{{jct|state=MI|US|31}} \u2013 running north from [[South Bend, Indiana]], enters the southeast county as the [[St. Joseph Valley Parkway]], near [[Niles, Michigan|Niles]], and continues north and west. A segment of the freeway was completed in August 2003, running from [[Berrien Springs, Michigan|Berrien Springs]] north to Napier Avenue east of Benton Harbor. US&nbsp;31 follows Napier Avenue west to I-94 before branching off with I-196. A final segment is planned to continue the freeway from Napier Avenue north to the junction with I-94 and BL I-94 with a full [[cloverleaf interchange]]. The former route of US&nbsp;31 between Berrien Springs and St. Joseph was redesignated as M-139.\n*{{jct|state=MI|M|51}} \u2013 enters from Indiana as a continuation of [[State Road 933 (Indiana)|State Road 933]]. Runs north through Niles, then northeast toward [[Dowagiac, Michigan]].\n*{{jct|state=MI|M|60}} \u2013 runs east from Niles to I-94 at [[Jackson, Michigan|Jackson]].\n*{{jct|state=MI|M|62}} \u2013 from its intersection with M-140, runs east toward [[Dowagiac, Michigan]].\n*{{jct|state=MI|M|63}} \u2013 from its intersection with M-139 (formerly US&nbsp;31) in [[Scottdale, Michigan|Scottdale]], runs northwest into St. Joseph, then northeast to intersection with US&nbsp;31/I-196 near the county line.\n*{{jct|state=MI|M|139}} \u2013 from its intersection with US&nbsp;31 near Berrien Springs, runs northwest to [[Scottdale, Michigan|Scottdale]], then north near St. Joseph and Benton Harbor to intersection with Business Loop I-94.\n*{{jct|state=MI|M|140}} \u2013 from Niles, runs north through the eastern part of the county toward [[South Haven, Michigan]].\n*{{jct|state=MI|M|239}} \u2013 its {{convert|1.1|mi|km}} length links I-94 at exit 1 near New Buffalo to [[State Road 39 (Indiana)|State Road 39]] north of [[LaPorte, Indiana]].\n*{{jct|state=MI|CDH|A-2}} \u2013 Berrien County's only signed county highway. Begins in [[Lake Michigan Beach, Michigan|Hagar Shores]] at M-63 and I-196. It follows the Lake Michigan shoreline and continues to [[South Haven, Michigan]].\n\n===Adjacent counties===\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n* [[Van Buren County, Michigan|Van Buren County]] \u2013 north and northeast\n* [[Cass County, Michigan|Cass County]] \u2013 east\n* [[St. Joseph County, Indiana]] \u2013 southeast\n* [[LaPorte County, Indiana]] \u2013 south\n* [[Porter County, Indiana]] \u2013 southwest\n* [[Cook County, Illinois]] \u2013 west\n* [[Lake County, Illinois]] \u2013 northwest\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1830= 325\n|1840= 5011\n|1850= 11417\n|1860= 22378\n|1870= 35104\n|1880= 36785\n|1890= 41285\n|1900= 49165\n|1910= 53622\n|1920= 62653\n|1930= 81066\n|1940= 89117\n|1950= 115702\n|1960= 149865\n|1970= 163875\n|1980= 171276\n|1990= 161378\n|2000= 162453\n|2010= 156813\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=154141\n|estref=<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/community_facts.xhtml|title=American FactFinder|accessdate=April 18, 2019|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108154236/https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|archivedate=January 8, 2017}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=US Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=US Decennial Census|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=September 19, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015}}</ref><br>1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=September 19, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120811110448/http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu/|archivedate=August 11, 2012}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/mi190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=September 19, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215142038/http://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/mi190090.txt|archivedate=February 15, 2015}}</ref><br>1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=September 19, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218203824/http://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|archivedate=December 18, 2014}}</ref> 2010-2018<ref name=QF/>\n}}\n\nThe [[2010 United States Census]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|title=American Factfinder| publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=March 11, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110620205543/http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|archivedate=June 20, 2011}}</ref> indicates Berrien County had a 2010 population of 156,813. This is a decrease of 5,640 people from the [[2000 United States Census]], or a 3.5% population decrease. In 2010 there were 63,054 households and 41,585 families in the county. The [[population density]] was 276.2 per square mile (106.6 square kilometers). There were 76,922 housing units at an average density of 135.5 per square mile (52.3 square kilometers). 78.3% of the population were [[White American|White]], 15.3% [[African American|Black or African American]], 1.6% [[Asian American|Asian]], 0.5% [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]], 0.1% [[Pacific Islands American|Pacific Islander]], 1.8% of some other race and 2.4% [[Multiracial American|of two or more races]]. 4.5% were [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic or Latino]] (of any race). 29.0% were of [[German American|German]], 7.4% [[Irish American|Irish]], 6.8% [[English American|English]] and 5.5% [[American ethnicity|American]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml###|title=American FactFinder|first=US Census|last=Bureau|website=factfinder2.census.gov|accessdate=May 5, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110620205543/http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|archivedate=June 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThere were 63,054 households, 29.6% of which had children under the age of 18 living with them, 47.8% were [[Family|husband and wife families]], 13.6% had a female householder with no husband present, 34.0% were non-families, and 28.7% were made up of individuals. The average household size was 2.43 and the average family size was 2.98.\n\nThe county population contained 23.4% under age of 18, 8.5% from 18 to 24, 23.2% from 25 to 44, 28.6% from 45 to 64, and 16.3% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 41 years. For every 100 females there were 94.9 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 91.6 males.\n\nThe [[American Community Survey|2010 American Community Survey 1-year estimate]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|title=American Factfinder|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=March 11, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110620205543/http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|archivedate=June 20, 2011}}</ref> indicates the median income for a household in the county was $40,329 and the median income for a family was $51,305. Males had a median income of $26,745 versus $16,289 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the county was $22,337. About 12.1% of families and 16.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 28.5% of those under the age 18 and 8.3% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Recreation==\n===State parks===\n*[[Grand Mere State Park]]\n*[[Warren Dunes State Park]]\n*[[Warren Woods State Park]]\n\n===Other parks===\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*[[Galien River]] County Park Preserve\n*Kiwanis Park \u2013 [[St. Joseph, Michigan|St. Joseph]]\n*Love Creek County Park\n*Madeline Bertrand County Park\n*Riverview Park \u2013 St. Joseph\n*Rocky Gap County Park\n*[[Silver Beach Amusement Park|Silver Beach County Park]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Resorts and beaches===\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*Hagar Park \u2013 [[Hagar Township, Michigan|Hagar Township]]\n*[[Jean Klock Park]] - [[Benton Harbor, Michigan|Benton Harbor]]\n*Lion\u2019s Park Beach \u2013 St. Joseph\n*New Buffalo Beach Park \u2013 [[New Buffalo, Michigan|New Buffalo]]\n*[[Paw Paw Lake]]\n*Rocky Gap Beach Park - Benton Harbor\n*Silver Beach - St. Joseph\n*Tiscornia Park\n*Weko Beach - [[Bridgman, Michigan|Bridgman]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Golf courses===\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*[[The Golf Club at Harbor Shores]] - Benton Harbor\n*Blossom Trails Golf Club \u2013 Benton Harbor\n*Brookwood Golf Course - [[Buchanan, Michigan|Buchanan]]\n*Lake Michigan Hills Golf Club - Benton Harbor\n*Lost Dunes Golf Club - Bridgman\n*Milan Creek Golf Club - Baroda\n*Orchard Hills Country Club - Buchanan\n*Paw Paw Lake Golf Club - Coloma/Watervliet\n*Pebblewood Country Club - Bridgman\n*Pipestone Creek Golf Course - Eau Claire\n*[[Point O'Woods Golf & Country Club]] - Benton Harbor\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Wineries===\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*12 Corners Vineyards - [[Benton Harbor, Michigan|Benton Harbor]]\n*Baroda Founders Wine Cellar - [[Baroda, Michigan|Baroda]]\n*Contessa Wine Cellars - [[Coloma, Michigan|Coloma]]\n*Dablon Winery and Vineyard - [[Baroda, Michigan|Baroda]]\n*Domaine Berrien Cellars \u2013 [[Berrien Springs, Michigan|Berrien Springs]]\n*Free Run Cellars - [[Berrien Springs, Michigan|Berrien Springs]]\n*Gravity - [[Baroda, Michigan|Baroda]]\n*Hickory Creek Winery - [[Buchanan, Michigan|Buchanan]]\n*Karma Vista Vineyards - [[Coloma, Michigan|Coloma]]\n*Lazy Ballerina Winery - [[St. Joseph, Michigan|St. Joseph]]\n*Lemon Creek Winery \u2013 [[Berrien Springs, Michigan|Berrien Springs]]\n*Round Barn Winery, Distillery & Brewery - [[Baroda, Michigan|Baroda]]\n*Tabor Hill Winery and Restaurant - [[Buchanan, Michigan|Buchanan]]\n*White Pine Winery - [[St. Joseph, Michigan|St. Joseph]]\n*Vineyard 2121 - [[Benton Harbor, Michigan|Benton Harbor]]\n*Red Top Winery - [[Baroda, Michigan|Baroda]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Communities==\n===Cities===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n*[[Benton Harbor, Michigan|Benton Harbor]]\n*[[Bridgman, Michigan|Bridgman]]\n*[[Buchanan, Michigan|Buchanan]]\n*[[Coloma, Michigan|Coloma]]\n*[[New Buffalo, Michigan|New Buffalo]]\n*[[Niles, Michigan|Niles]]\n*[[St. Joseph, Michigan|St. Joseph]] (county seat)\n*[[Watervliet, Michigan|Watervliet]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Villages===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n*[[Baroda, Michigan|Baroda]]\n*[[Berrien Springs, Michigan|Berrien Springs]]\n*[[Eau Claire, Michigan|Eau Claire]]\n*[[Galien, Michigan|Galien]]\n*[[Grand Beach, Michigan|Grand Beach]]\n*[[Michiana, Michigan|Michiana]]\n*[[Shoreham, Michigan|Shoreham]]\n*[[Stevensville, Michigan|Stevensville]]\n*[[Three Oaks, Michigan|Three Oaks]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Census-designated places===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n*[[Benton Heights, Michigan|Benton Heights]]\n*[[Fair Plain, Michigan|Fair Plain]]\n*[[Lake Michigan Beach, Michigan|Lake Michigan Beach]]\n*[[New Troy, Michigan|New Troy]]\n*[[Paw Paw Lake, Michigan|Paw Paw Lake]]\n*[[Shorewood-Tower Hills-Harbert, Michigan|Shorewood-Tower Hills-Harbert]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Unincorporated communities===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n*[[Berrien Center, Michigan|Berrien Center]]\n*[[Bethany Beach, Michigan|Bethany Beach]]\n*[[Birchwood, Michigan|Birchwood]]\n*[[Dayton, Berrien County, Michigan|Dayton]]\n*[[Glendora, Michigan|Glendora]]\n*[[Harbert, Michigan|Harbert]]\n*[[Hazelhurst, Michigan|Hazelhurst]]\n*[[Hinchman, Michigan|Hinchman]]\n*Hollywood, Michigan\n*[[Lakeside, Berrien County, Michigan|Lakeside]]\n*[[Millburg, Michigan|Millburg]]\n*[[Lakeside, Berrien County, Michigan|Riverside]]\n*[[Sawyer, Michigan|Sawyer]]\n*[[Scottdale, Michigan|Scottdale]]\n*[[Shorewood Hills, Michigan|Shorewood Hills]]\n*[[Tower Hill Shorelands, Michigan|Tower Hill Shorelands]]\n*[[Union Pier, Michigan|Union Pier]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Townships===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n*[[Bainbridge Township, Michigan|Bainbridge Township]]\n*[[Baroda Township, Michigan|Baroda Township]]\n*[[Benton Charter Township, Michigan|Benton Charter Township]]\n*[[Berrien Township, Michigan|Berrien Township]]\n*[[Bertrand Township, Michigan|Bertrand Township]]\n*[[Buchanan Township, Michigan|Buchanan Township]]\n*[[Chikaming Township, Michigan|Chikaming Township]]\n*[[Coloma Charter Township, Michigan|Coloma Charter Township]]\n*[[Galien Township, Michigan|Galien Township]]\n*[[Hagar Township, Michigan|Hagar Township]]\n*[[Lake Charter Township, Michigan|Lake Charter Township]]\n*[[Lincoln Charter Township, Michigan|Lincoln Charter Township]]\n*[[New Buffalo Township, Michigan|New Buffalo Township]]\n*[[Niles Township, Michigan|Niles Charter Township]]\n*[[Oronoko Charter Township, Michigan|Oronoko Charter Township]]\n*[[Pipestone Township, Michigan|Pipestone Township]]\n*[[Royalton Township, Michigan|Royalton Township]]\n*[[Sodus Township, Michigan|Sodus Township]]\n*[[St. Joseph Charter Township, Michigan|St. Joseph Charter Township]]\n*[[Three Oaks Township, Michigan|Three Oaks Township]]\n*[[Watervliet Township, Michigan|Watervliet Charter Township]]\n*[[Weesaw Township, Michigan|Weesaw Township]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Indian reservation===\n[[File:Pokagon Band of Potawatomi Indians (Berrien County), MI location.png|thumb|right|250px|The Pokagon reservation with underlying local municipal boundaries]]\n*The [[Pokagon Band of Potawatomi Indians]] has a reservation occupying a portion of the southeastern corner of Berrien County.  The tribe also occupies areas in [[Allegan County, Michigan|Allegan]], [[Cass County, Michigan|Cass]], and [[Van Buren County, Michigan|Van Buren]] counties, as well as extending south into the state of [[Indiana]].  The reservation headquarters are located in neighboring Cass County in the city of [[Dowagiac, Michigan|Dowagiac]].<ref>{{cite web|last=[[Pokagon Band of Potawatomi Indians]]|title=Pok\u00e9gnek Bod\u00e9wadmik (Pokagon Band of Potawatomi)|url=http://www.pokagon.com/|date=2019|accessdate=January 3, 2019}}</ref>  The Berrien County reservation surrounds the entire portion of the city of [[Niles, Michigan|Niles]] that lies within the county, as well as portions of [[Bertrand Township, Michigan|Bertrand Township]] and [[Niles Charter Township, Michigan|Niles Charter Township]] along the [[St. Joseph River (Lake Michigan)|St. Joseph River]].<ref>{{cite web|last=[[United States Census Bureau]]|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/maps/general_ref/cousub_outline/cen2k_pgsz/mi_cosub.pdf|title=Michigan County Subdivision Outline Map|date=2000|accessdate=April 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Michigan State Historic Sites in Berrien County, Michigan]]\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Berrien County, Michigan]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.berriencounty.org/ Berrien County government \u2013 official web site]\n*[http://www.bchdmi.org/ Berrien County Health Department]\n*[http://bcroad.org/ Berrien County Road Department]\n*[http://www.bcsheriff.org/ Berrien County Sheriff's Department]\n*[http://berrien.usaroots.com Berrien County GenGuide] f